johnn@eskimo.com (John Navitsky) writes:

>Considering the limitation of ~3 PCI slots on current motherboards, a
>PCI/EISA combo would seem the best choice for servers.  Run video & two
>SCSI controllers off PCI, network off EISA, pick up any more SCSI & network
>off EISA.  Any thoughts?

Currently EISA is still relevant for servers but I don't think that there is
still much development for the EISA bus. 

You can overcome the PCI slot limitation by strapping serveral PCI buses
together. Use the first 8 loads to connect to 6 slave busses and you can
have as many slots as your main board can handle. The idea of a slave PCI
bus is already implemented in network cards which integrate 4 ethernet cards
and a secondary PCI bus on just one PCI card. 

